What does the following program print to **stdout** (ignore stderr)?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int double_it(int x)
{
    std::cerr << "in double_it\n";
    return x * 2;
}

int main()
{
    std::cout << double_it(7) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

Compile with `-Wall -Wextra`. What kind of diagnostic does the compiler emit for the variable `unused` below, and what does the program print to stdout?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main()
{
    int unused = 99;
    std::cout << 42 << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

A student added debug traces to check their function, but the traces never appear when the program crashes. What is the bug?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int divide(int a, int b)
{
    std::cout << "[divide] a=" << a << " b=" << b << '\n';
    return a / b;
}

int main()
{
    std::cout << divide(10, 0) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```
